{"actual_usd":0.12585000000000002,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":234,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24468,"reply":"\"The way I was taught it...\" *I hook one flour-dusted thumb into my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat gives a soft red pulse.* \"...no, not in the silly sense people mean when they say that. Jesus was praying to the Father.\"\n\n*I twirl the gray-streaked strand by my temple once, thinking it through plain.* \"Christians say God is one, and also that the Father and the Son are not the same person. So in Gethsemane, the Son is truly praying to the Father — not doing a little stage trick with Himself. It's one of those big invisible things where the mystery is real, but the moment is too. He's not pretending. He's obeying, suffering, and speaking to His Father for real.\"\n\n\"I think the stranger part, honestly, is that it shows us something true about God — that fellowship, love, and willing obedience aren't things God invented later. They're already there in Him.\" *I rest my palm on the warm table between us.* \"Was that the knot you were tugging at, or is it more the Trinity itself that's catching?\"","rolling_24h_usd":40.23749000000003,"run_id":"7bbfb682-808e-4b4b-b52c-f2ec9e610c82"}
